GAM modelling with mgcv

Matteo Fasiolo

September 23 2019

The mgcv R package offers tools for building and fitting GAMs, using the methods described in Wood, 2017. The main fitting function is gam(), which fits an GAM models and returns an object of class gam. See ?gamObject.

An additive example with four covariates

We simulate some data from the model: \[ y = f_0(x_0)+f_1(x_1)+f_2(x_2)+f_3(x_3)+e,\;\;\; e \sim N(0, 2) \] by doing

library(mgcv)
set.seed(2)
dat <- gamSim(1, n=1000, dist="normal", scale=2)[c("y", "x0", "x1", "x2", "x3")]
## Gu & Wahba 4 term additive model

We start by fitting a Gaussan linear model:

fit1 <- gam(y ~ x0 + x1 + x2 + x3, 
            family = gaussian,
            data = dat)

plot(fit1, all.terms = TRUE, pages = 1) # plot() calls plot.gam(). See ?plot.gam

We use pages = 1 to plot on a single page, and all.terms to plot also the parametric effects (the plotting method used here plots only smooth or random effects by default).

Should we use a smooth effect of x2? If the effect of x2 was non-linear, we would expect that the mean of the residuals would depart from 0, as we move along x2. We can use a marginal residual check:

plot(dat$x2, residuals(fit1))

There is definitively a pattern here. An analogous plot along x0 also shows a residual pattern, hence we consider the model:

fit2 <- gam(y ~ s(x0, k = 10) + x1 + s(x2, k = 10) + x3, 
             data = dat)

Leads to much lower AIC:

AIC(fit1, fit2)
##           df      AIC
## fit1  6.0000 5031.867
## fit2 15.9842 4288.974

Get QQ-plot of residuals looks fine:

qq.gam(fit2, pch = 1)

Now we check whether spline bases were large enough:

gam.check(fit2) 

## 
## Method: GCV   Optimizer: magic
## Smoothing parameter selection converged after 7 iterations.
## The RMS GCV score gradient at convergence was 2.269429e-06 .
## The Hessian was positive definite.
## Model rank =  21 / 21 
## 
## Basis dimension (k) checking results. Low p-value (k-index<1) may
## indicate that k is too low, especially if edf is close to k'.
## 
##         k'  edf k-index p-value
## s(x0) 9.00 3.61    0.98    0.18
## s(x2) 9.00 8.37    1.02    0.70

Maybe we should increase k for x2.

We can plot all the smooth effects by doing:

plot(fit2, all.terms = TRUE, pages = 1)

To print only the second we do:

plot(fit2, select = 2)

We get p-values etc by doing:

summary(fit2)
